    <Placemark>
        <name>EDF Action 2026 Environmental Book Club</name>
        <description><![CDATA[
<h3>EDF Action 2026 Environmental Book Club</h3>
<p><strong>When:</strong> Saturday, March 14, 2026 at 4:00 PM UTC - 5:00 PM</p>
<p><strong>Where:</strong><br>Location not specified</p>
<p><strong>Organized by:</strong> EDF Action</p>
<p><strong>About:</strong></p><p>Join us the second Saturday of each month for our environmental book club!  We will be discussing these books and documentaries in 2026: 

JAN: Here Comes the Sun
By Bill McKibben 
Available on Amazon Paperback and Audible audio book 

The book explores the rapid, cheap growth of solar and wind power and how it offers humanity a genuine, hopeful chance to overcome the climate crisis and build a better civilization, despite fossil fuel industry opposition.

FEB:  A Future We Can Love 
By Susan Bauer-Wu 
Available on Amazon paperback + free audio book with Audible membership

Inspired by a conversation between the Dalai Lama and Greta Thunberg spoke for the first time in January 2021, millions of people around the world took notice. This book captures the lessons that came from that interaction. 


MAR: The Fragile Earth
By David Remnick, Henry Finder 
Available at local library, Hoopla and Amazon Paperback or Audible audio book

A collection of essays that tell the story of climate change—its past, present, and future—taking readers from Greenland to the Great Plains, and into both laboratories and rain forests.

APR: The Genius of Earth Day
By Adam Rome
Available at local library, Hoopla, Amazon + free audiobook with Audible membership.

The story of the first Earth Day is inspiring: it had a power, a freshness, and a seriousness of purpose that are difficult to imagine today. Earth Day 1970 created an entire green generation. 

MAY:  Amplify
By Adam Met 
Available on Amazon in paperback or Audible audio book

A musician and member of the multiplatinum band AJR, Adam Met is also a climate advocate and educator, who shows how to apply fan-building strategies to social movements in exciting, inventive ways. Amplify is a playbook for developing passionate supporters utilizing the art and science of engagement, collaboration, and authentic connection, with tactics that will inspire people to carry a climate message to the world and spur others to act.

JUN: Unsettled 
by Steven Koonin 
Available at the local library, on Hoopla and Amazon Paperback or Audible audio book

Koonin was the top science advisor to the Obama administration.  When it comes to climate change, the media, politicians, and other prominent voices have declared that “the science is settled.” In reality, the climate is changing, but the why and how aren’t as clear as you’ve probably been led to believe. Koonin takes listeners behind the headlines, dispels popular myths, and unveils little-known truths. 

JUL: Documentary:  Ice on Fire
Free on Youtube (1:37)
(https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AP2IE8Upehc) 
Narrated by Leonardo DiCaprio

&quot;Ice on Fire&quot; explores the many ways we reduce carbon inputs to the atmosphere and, more importantly, how to &quot;draw&quot; carbon down, bringing CO2 out of the atmosphere and thus paving the way for global temperatures to go down. Through visiting visionaries and scientists young and old, the film explores the deep hope that we can turn away from the brink.  

AUG: Running Out 
By Lucas Bessire
Available at the local library, on Hoopla and Amazon Paperback

The imminent depletion of the Ogallala and other aquifers around the world is a defining planetary crisis of our times. Running Out explores aquifer depletion and the deeper layers through which it gains meaning and force. Anthropologist Lucas Bessire journeyed back to Western Kansas, where five generations of his family lived as irrigation farmers and ranchers, to try to make sense of this vital resource and its loss.

SEPT: Half Earth 
By Edward O. Wilson 
Available at the local library, on Hoopla and Amazon Paperback + Audiobook

In order to stave off the mass extinction of species, including our own, we must move swiftly to preserve the biodiversity of our planet. In this &quot;visionary blueprint for saving the planet&quot; (Stephen Greenblatt), Half-Earth argues that the situation facing us is too large to be solved piecemeal and proposes a solution commensurate with the magnitude of the problem: dedicate fully half the surface of the Earth to nature. 

OCT: The Boy Who Harnessed the Wind (watch the movie or read the book)
Movie: Find it on Youtube or Netflix 
Book: Available at the local library, on Hoopla and Amazon Paperback + Audiobook

Born to a family of farmers, Malawian agricultural engineer William Kamkwamba made headlines in 2001 when he built a functioning windmill out of old bicycle parts and scraps. (At the time, he was just 14 years old.) The Boy Who Harnessed the Wind, based on Kamkwamba’s memoir of the same name, tells the amazing true story of how he built a wind turbine and saved his small farming village from famine.

NOV: The Talking Earth (young adult)
by Jean George 
Available at the local library, on Hoopla and Amazon Paperback + Audiobook

Billie is a member of the Seminole Tribe, in a quest to identify facts over legend, she goes out into the Everglades alone, to stay until she can believe. In the wilderness, she discovers that she must listen to the land and animals in order to survive. With an otter, a panther cub, and a turtle as companions and guides, she begins to understand that the world of her people can give her the answers she seeks.

DEC:  A look back at our list of books - what did we learn? What is most memorable from our reading? 

_________________________________________________________
BOOK CLUB 2025 (For reference only) 

January 11th: [Documentary] Living the Change: Inspiring Stories for a Sustainable Future (Free Full Documentary)

February 8th: [Book] No is Not Enough, by Naomi Klein (Available on amazon, Hoopla, local library)

March 8th: [Book] The Language of Climate Politics, by Genevieve Guenther (available on amazon, Hoopla and local library)

April 12th: [Book] Silent Spring - Rachel Carson Let’s revisit the book that started our book club AND the environmental movement!

May 10th: [Podcast] How to save a planet - listen to a few episodes and come to the meeting to share what you learned. (https://gimletmedia.com/shows/howtosaveaplanet/episodes#show-tab-picker) find it on spotify: https://open.spotify.com/show/1KzrasExlM5dgMYwgFHns6

June 14th: [Book] It’s not that Radical | climate action to transform our world - Mikaela Loach

July 12th: [Documentary]: Climate extremes (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U8pLrRkqbb0)

August 9th: [Book] Earth for All, by Sandrine Dixson Decleve (available on Amazon)

September 13th: [Book] What if We Get it Right, by Ayana Elizabeth Johnson (Available in book and audio on Amazon)

October 11th: [Podcast] Climate Rising (https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/a-preview-of-cop29-what-business-leaders-should/id1482781075?i=1000675873770)

November 8th: [Book] The Good Ancestor, by Roman Krznaric (available on Amazon and Hoopla audio)

December 13th: Year end wrap up - what did we learn? 2026 Book Club</p>
<p><a href="https://www.mobilize.us/event/876655/" target="_blank">View Event on Mobilize.us</a></p>
<p><i>Data source: mobilize.us | Updated: 2026-02-18T07:03:09.039Z</i></p>
]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#no_location</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
